    "markdown": "---\ntitle: \"Lecture 1.2 Root Finding Methods: Bisection Method\"\ndescription: \"Bisection Method\"\ndate: 2025-03-30\ncategories: [numerical-analysis, python]\nimage: bisection_method_ilustration.png\n---\n\n## Overview\n\nBisection method is one of the most powerful methods because we can stimate the number of steps that are necessary to guarantee at least certain tolerance $\\epsilon$. \n\n**Important idea**: Just as in the search method, we continue to look for a change in the sign of the function. But now, let’s imagine we have an interval $[a,b]$. First, we calculate the midpoint $c$ between $a$ and $b$. Next, we apply Bolzano’s theorem to $[a,c]$ and $[c,b]$; depending on our results, the new interval will be one of those two. \n\n## Theoretical Basis and Demonstrations\n\nRemenber Bolzano's theorem:\n\nLet $f$ be a continuous function on a closed interval $[a, b]$. If $f(a) \\cdot f(b) < 0$, then:\n\n$$\n\\exists \\alpha \\in (a, b) \\text{ such that } f(\\alpha) = 0\n$$\n\nThe bisection method generates a secuence \n$$\n\\{s_n\\}_{n=1}^{\\infty} \\quad\n$$\n\nthat aproximates to $\\alpha$ with:\n\n$$\n|s_n - \\alpha| \\leq \\frac{b - a}{2^n}, \\text{when n}\\leq 1\n$$\n\nWhere the aproximate root $s_n$ is \n\n$$\n\\frac{b_{n-1} + a_{n-1}}{2}\n$$\n\nTo reach an accuracy of \n\n$$\n|s_n - \\alpha| \\leq \\epsilon\n$$\n\nWe only need to take\n$$\nn > \\frac{\\ln(b - a) - \\ln(\\epsilon)}{\\ln(2)}\n$$\n\n**Time to prove**\n\nLet be $[a_1, b_1]$ the initial interval, its length $L = b_1 - a_1 = b - a$, the inicial mid point is $a_1$\n\nApplying induction over the length, in each step we divide the curretn interval.\n\n$n = 1$, $L = \\frac{b-a}{2}$\n\n$n=2$, $L= \\frac{1}{2} (\\frac{b-a}{2})= \\frac{b-a}{2^2}$\n\n...\n\n$n=2$, $[a_n, b_n]= \\frac{b-a}{2^{n-1}}$\n\nNotice that the exponent is $n-1$ because in $n = 1$, the length has been reduced once respect to the original or $2^n$ if the consider the absolute error from the start. \n\nNow, we know that $\\alpha \\in [a_n, b_n]$, the aproximation $s_n$ is the mid point of the interval: \n\n$$\ns_n = \\frac{a_n-b_n}{2}\n$$\n\nGeometrically, the maximun distance from $s_n$ to any extreme point is the half of the current interval.\n\n$$\n\\therefore |s_n - \\alpha| \\leq \\frac{1}{2}(b_n - a_n) = \\frac{1}{2}\\frac{b - a}{2^{n-1}} = \\frac{b - a}{2^n}\n$$\n\nRember we said that \n$$\n|s_n - \\alpha| \\leq \\epsilon\n$$\n\n$$\n\\implies \\frac{2^n}{b-a}>\\frac{1}{\\epsilon}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\implies 2^n>\\frac{b-a}{\\epsilon}\n$$\n\n$$\n\\implies \\ln(2^n)>\\ln(\\frac{b-a}{\\epsilon})\n$$\n\n$$\n\\implies n>\\frac{\\ln(\\frac{b-a}{\\epsilon})}{\\ln(2)}\n$$\n\nor also:\n\n$$\nn> \\log_2 \\frac{b-a}{\\epsilon}\n$$\n\n## Convergence Order\n\nThe convergence order determines the rate at which a sequence of approximations converges to the true solution.\n\nLet be the real error $E_n = | s_n - \\alpha |$, a sequence converges to $\\alpha$ with a convergence order $\\tau$ and a asintotic error constant called $\\lambda$ ($\\lambda>0$) if it satifies the following limit:\n\n$$\n\\lim_{n \\to \\infty} \\frac{|s_{n+1} - \\alpha|}{|s_n - \\alpha|^\\tau} = \\lim_{n \\to \\infty} \\frac{E_{n+1}}{(E_n)^\\tau} = \\lambda\n$$\n\nIn the worsth case:\n$$\n|e_{n+1}| \\approx \\frac{1}{2} |e_n|\n$$\n\n$$\n\\implies \\tau = 1 \\text{ and } \\lambda = 0.5\n$$\n\nDue to the fact $\\tau = 1$, we say that the algorithm converges linearly.\n\n## The algorithm\n\nThe logic can be summarized in the following steps:\n\nFor $n = 1, 2, 3, \\dots$:\n\nThe mid point in the $n$ iteration is defined as $s_n = \\frac{a_n + b_n}{2}$.1\n\n* Evaluate $f(s_n)$.\n\n* If $f(s_n) = 0$ or $\\frac{b_n - a_n}{2} < \\epsilon$, stop the algorithm; $s_n$ is the root.\n\n* If $f(a_n) \\cdot f(s_n) < 0$, root is in the left half. Hence $a_{n+1} = a_n$ and $b_{n+1} = s_n$.\n\n* If not , the root is in the rigth half. Hence $a_{n+1} = s_n$ and $b_{n+1} = b_n$.\n\n## Hands on\n\nHere, you will see two important concepts, **Theorical bound** and the **Real error**, this code is designed to show you this difference. \n\n::: {#60a25059 .cell execution_count=1}\n``` {.python .cell-code code-fold=\"true\" code-summary=\"See implementation\"}\nimport pandas as pd\nimport numpy as np\n\n# ─── Quadratic parameters ──────────────────────────\nA, B, C = 2.0, 6.0, 2.0   # f(x) = x² - 3x + 2\nf = lambda x: A*x**2 + B*x + C\n\n# ─── Analytical solution ───────────────────────────\ndiscriminant = B**2 - 4*A*C\nroot1 = (-B + np.sqrt(discriminant)) / (2*A)\nroot2 = (-B - np.sqrt(discriminant)) / (2*A)\nprint(f\"f(x) = {A}x² - {B}x + {C}\")\nprint(f\"Analytical roots: x₁ = {root1}, x₂ = {root2}\")\n\n# ─── Bisection setup ───────────────────────────────\na, b = 1.5, 3.0    # interval containing root1\nalpha = root1       # exact root for error comparison\nepsilon = 1e-6\n\ndef bisection(f, a, b, epsilon, alpha):\n    historial = []\n    n = 1\n    n_min = np.ceil((np.log(b - a) - np.log(epsilon)) / np.log(2))\n    print(f\"Minimum iterations required: {int(n_min)}\")\n\n    while True:\n        sn = (a + b) / 2\n        fsn = f(sn)\n        en_bound = (b - a) / 2              # theoretical bound\n        en_real  = abs(sn - alpha)          # real error\n\n        historial.append({\n            \"n\": n,\n            \"a\": round(a, 6),\n            \"b\": round(b, 6),\n            \"sn\": round(sn, 6),\n            \"f(sn)\": round(fsn, 6),\n            \"Theoretical bound\": round(en_bound, 8),\n            \"Real error\": round(en_real, 8),\n        })\n\n        if fsn == 0 or en_bound < epsilon:\n            print(f\"Root found: sn = {sn:.8f} after {n} iterations\")\n            break\n\n        if f(a) * fsn < 0:\n            b = sn\n        else:\n            a = sn\n\n        n += 1\n\n    return sn, pd.DataFrame(historial)\n\nroot, df = bisection(f, a, b, epsilon, alpha)\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}\n```\nf(x) = 2.0x² - 6.0x + 2.0\nAnalytical roots: x₁ = -0.3819660112501051, x₂ = -2.618033988749895\nMinimum iterations required: 21\nRoot found: sn = 2.99999928 after 21 iterations\n```\n:::\n:::\n\n\n## Iterations\n\n::: {#d767994c .cell execution_count=2}\n\n::: {.cell-output .cell-output-display execution_count=2}\n```{=html}\n<div>\n<style scoped>\n    .dataframe tbody tr th:only-of-type {\n        vertical-align: middle;\n    }\n\n    .dataframe tbody tr th {\n        vertical-align: top;\n    }\n\n    .dataframe thead th {\n        text-align: right;\n    }\n</style>\n<table border=\"1\" class=\"dataframe\">\n  <thead>\n    <tr style=\"text-align: right;\">\n      <th></th>\n      <th>n</th>\n      <th>a</th>\n      <th>b</th>\n      <th>sn</th>\n      <th>f(sn)</th>\n      <th>Theoretical bound</th>\n      <th>Real error</th>\n    </tr>\n  </thead>\n  <tbody>\n    <tr>\n      <th>0</th>\n      <td>1</td>\n      <td>1.500000</td>\n      <td>3.0</td>\n      <td>2.250000</td>\n      <td>25.625000</td>\n      <td>7.500000e-01</td>\n      <td>2.631966</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>1</th>\n      <td>2</td>\n      <td>2.250000</td>\n      <td>3.0</td>\n      <td>2.625000</td>\n      <td>31.531250</td>\n      <td>3.750000e-01</td>\n      <td>3.006966</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>2</th>\n      <td>3</td>\n      <td>2.625000</td>\n      <td>3.0</td>\n      <td>2.812500</td>\n      <td>34.695312</td>\n      <td>1.875000e-01</td>\n      <td>3.194466</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>3</th>\n      <td>4</td>\n      <td>2.812500</td>\n      <td>3.0</td>\n      <td>2.906250</td>\n      <td>36.330078</td>\n      <td>9.375000e-02</td>\n      <td>3.288216</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>4</th>\n      <td>5</td>\n      <td>2.906250</td>\n      <td>3.0</td>\n      <td>2.953125</td>\n      <td>37.160645</td>\n      <td>4.687500e-02</td>\n      <td>3.335091</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>5</th>\n      <td>6</td>\n      <td>2.953125</td>\n      <td>3.0</td>\n      <td>2.976562</td>\n      <td>37.579224</td>\n      <td>